The world born from September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th commemoration of the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, in the United States.
That day, 19 terrorists took control of four civilian airplanes, hijacked two of the planes and crashed them into the World Trade Center towers in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and then diverted a fourth plane to crash in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another U.S. government building in Washington, DC.
All the airline hijackers were from the Middle East, and 15 were from Saudi Arabia.
All of them had been trained in Afghanistan, and four had been trained in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and executed operation by Al-Qaïda (the "base"), the terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
By the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children had been killed, and over 6,000 were injured.
Most were American, although citizens from more than a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
At the time, many feared that September 11 had ushered in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaïda followed, including several bombings on trains in Madrid in March 2004, and the attack on London's public transportation in July 2005.
Terrorists affiliated with the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and carried out a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to run over pedestrians).
Nevertheless, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable scale to those of September 11 – which were unparalleled.
It is therefore worth asking: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why terrorists have not been able to carry out other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaïda lost its sanctuary.
Nearly all governments around the world have implemented control procedures making it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the few areas in which states often in disagreement are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is now also a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments cannot make a distinction between terrorists and those who provide them sanctuary and support.
The days when individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters are over.
It is not claiming that terrorism has ceased to claim tens of thousands of lives each year.
Nevertheless, nearly all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of current conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks, of the 9/11 type, against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist group's leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaïda, for example, survived the elimination of Bin Laden by U.S. special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution to the problem on the horizon.
The possibility of a new 9/11 cannot also be ruled out, although the U.S. government has recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country exists domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today, we have not been lucky, but remember that it only takes one chance."
You will need to have that luck always."
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists may get their hands on nuclear material, or succeed in creating and using a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could determine the era.
For now, this is not the case.
September 11 nevertheless marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the past two decades.
If the attacks did not lead to an era of global terrorism, they did indeed generate the famous global war on terror, with major consequences for the behavior of the United States around the world, the image of America in the eyes of the world, and the way in which many Americans came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Shortly after the September 11 attacks, the United States presented the Taliban, who then controlled the Afghan government, with a choice: hand over the Al-Qaïda leaders on the verge of leaving the country, and guilty of organizing the September 11 attacks, or risk their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaïda leaders, U.S. intelligence and military forces collaborated with a loosely structured Afghan tribal confederation called the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States helped form a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control was never complete or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaïda took refuge in neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually regained strength and resumed their military operations against the government that had replaced them.
Meanwhile, the United States did not do enough to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, the United States strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, becoming essentially a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the United States' intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of the operations amounts to more than $2 trillion, for more than 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
United States presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persistent than the United States, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict destined to end only in an indefinite stalemate.
The global war on terrorism also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had phrased during the Vietnam War, a "pitiful and helpless giant."
This led some members of the administration (notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to reject the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (which, according to most participants, was not the case).
Others aimed to spread democracy in Iraq, and then throughout the Middle East, considering that this endeavor was not only feasible but would also make the region much less likely to produce and support terrorists.
The Iraq War, launched in March 2003, did not unfold as the Bush administration, as well as many members of Congress (including Joe Biden, then a senator) and global leaders who had approved it, had hoped or predicted.
The United States was not prepared for most of the events to come.
Military victories initially allowed the government to be ousted, but quickly gave way to widespread unrest as well as a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude from government jobs many Iraqis associated with the previous regime exacerbated an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, demonstrated the limits of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
In the end, the United States was forced to strengthen its military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability was achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but for a much heavier human toll: more than 4,000 American soldiers killed, a far greater number of wounded, and an explosive rate of suicide among American military personnel (in Iraq as well as in Afghanistan).
This total also excludes deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for whom estimates vary widely, but whose numbers certainly reach into the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq also weakened the United States in other respects.
No evidence has ever shown Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for military intervention without UN approval – aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction – proved to be based on no real foundation.
Images of American soldiers abusing Iraqi prisoners further tarnished the country's reputation.
Moreover, an Iraq at war with itself became synonymous with an Iran emerging as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if one considers Israel).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States was deeply involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the United States, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia and a stronger, more assertive China.
The global war on terrorism could not and did not provide the United States with a compass for its approach to foreign policy in the face of a renewed rivalry among great powers.
The wars following September 11 also led to significant domestic consequences for the United States.
They undermined the confidence of a country that had emerged from the Cold War as a historically unprecedented superpower, and eroded the national unity that had surfaced immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have also fueled opposition to a major and lasting global role for the United States, giving rise to a new trend of isolationism.
Similarly, this bellicose tendency, associated with the 2007-2009 global financial crisis and its economic repercussions, has seriously impacted Americans' trust in elites, thereby stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to the rise of Donald Trump.
Today's America is more divided than ever internally, and less and less willing to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans and many others overall.
In retrospect, we can today view September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less the globalization of terrorism than the terrors of globalization.
The attacks sent the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global age.
Nothing remains local for very long now, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis whose origins lie in poor American financial management.
We are all currently facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its emergence in China in December 2019.
Fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves devastating many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself a cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events concludes a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of the U.S. intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly removed from power; in recent weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know whether the Taliban will resume their old habits by becoming once again a sanctuary for terrorism, and whether terrorists around the world will take pride in their victory over the United States and its allies.
What we do know, on the other hand, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that already determines it.
